Alright, let's dissect this region. You want an article, not a conversation. Fine. Consider this a curated excavation of facts, delivered with the precision of a scalpel and the weary sigh of someone who's seen it all.

## Bengal

[Bengal](/Bengal) (pronounced /bɛnˈɡɔːl/ ben-GAWL) is a geographical, ethnolinguistic, and historically geopolitical region situated in the northeastern part of the [Indian subcontinent](/South_Asia). It lies to the north of the vast [Bay of Bengal](/Bay_of_Bengal). Today, this land is divided, a fractured reflection of its past, encompassing the sovereign nation of [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh), the Indian state of [West Bengal](/West_Bengal), and the [Karimganj district](/Karimganj_district) within the Indian state of [Assam](/Assam).

The ancient [Vanga Kingdom](/Vanga_Kingdom) is widely considered the origin of the region’s name, a foundational element in its long and complex identity. The [Bengali calendar](/Bengali_calendar), a testament to its enduring cultural traditions, traces its roots back to the 7th century CE, during the reign of [Shashanka](/Shashanka). The 8th century marked the rise of the [Pala Empire](/Pala_Empire) within Bengal, a significant dominion that would shape the region’s destiny. Following this, the [Sena dynasty](/Sena_dynasty) and the [Deva dynasty](/Deva_dynasty) held sway between the 11th and 13th centuries. By the 14th century, the tide of [Muslim conquests in the Indian subcontinent](/Muslim_conquests_in_the_Indian_subcontinent) brought Bengal under new rule, leading to the establishment of an independent [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate). This powerful entity served as the easternmost frontier of the [Islamic world](/Islamic_world), its influence extending to territories as far-reaching as [Assam](/Assam), [Arakan](/Arakan), [Tripura](/Tripura), [Bihar](/Bihar), and [Odisha](/Odisha) (formerly Orissa). Later, the [Bengal Subah](/Bengal_Subah) emerged as a remarkably prosperous and vital province within the expansive [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire).

The grip of independent rule was ultimately broken in 1757, when the last independent [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal) was defeated at the [Battle of Plassey](/Battle_of_Plassey) by the forces of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company). This marked the beginning of a new era, with the company's [Bengal Presidency](/Bengal_Presidency) evolving into the largest administrative division of [British India](/British_India). For a significant period, [Calcutta](/Calcutta) served as the dual capital of both Bengal and British India, until 1911. The ill-conceived [first partition of Bengal](/Partition_of_Bengal_(1905)) in 1905 led to the brief existence of the province of [Eastern Bengal and Assam](/Eastern_Bengal_and_Assam), with its administrative center in the historic city of [Dhaka](/Dhaka). The region was once again subjected to division in 1947, this time along religious lines following the [Sylhet referendum](/Sylhet_referendum,_1947) and subsequent legislative decisions by the [Bengal Legislative Council](/British_Bengal_Legislative_Council) and [Bengal Legislative Assembly](/Bengal_Legislative_Assembly_(1937%E2%80%941947)).

The cultural tapestry of Bengal, particularly its contributions to [literature](/Bengali_literature), [music](/Bengali_music), [art](/Bangladeshi_art), and cinema, is renowned across South Asia and beyond. The region has also been a cradle for distinguished economic and social thinkers, including several [Nobel laureates](/Nobel_laureate). Once a beacon of economic prosperity, boasting the highest per capita income in British India, Bengal today stands as a leader in South Asia in areas such as [gender parity](/Gender_Parity_Index), the reduction of the [gender pay gap](/Gender_pay_gap), and other crucial indicators of [human development](/Human_Development_Index).

### Etymology

• Main article: [Names of Bengal](/Names_of_Bengal)

The name "Bengal" is a derivative of the ancient kingdom of [Vanga](/Vanga_Kingdom), pronounced *Bôngô*. Earliest records of this kingdom can be traced back to the [Mahabharata](/Mahabharata) epic, dating from the [first millennium BCE](/First_millennium_BCE). Over time, the land of Vaṅga evolved into Vaṅgāla (*Bāṅgālā*). The earliest documented reference to this form appears in the [Comilla](/Comilla_District) copperplates from 720 CE, belonging to the Deva King Ananda Deva, where he is described as *Sri Vaṅgāla Mrīgānka*, signifying "the moon of Vaṅgāla." The term 'Vangalam' also finds mention in South Indian records from the 11th century, found within an inscription in the [Brihadisvara Temple](/Brihadisvara_Temple) at [Thanjavur](/Thanjavur), a significant early reference to the region. By the 12th century, the Sanskrit text [Manasollasa](/Manasollasa) used the name *Gaudabangala* to denote the entire [Bengal region](/Bengal_region). The modern appellation "Bangla" gained prominence from the 14th century, coinciding with the establishment of the [Sultanate of Bengal](/Sultanate_of_Bengal). Its inaugural ruler, [Shamsuddin Ilyas Shah](/Shamsuddin_Ilyas_Shah), was known as the *Shah* of Bangala. Prominent Arab geographers like [Ahmad ibn Majid](/Ahmad_ibn_Majid) and [Sulaiman Al Mahri](/Sulaiman_Al_Mahri) also referenced the region as 'Bangala,' the 'land of Bang.' The [Portuguese](/Portuguese_Empire), during their era of exploration, referred to the territory as Bengala.

### History

• Main article: [History of Bengal](/History_of_Bengal)

#### Antiquity

• See also: [Vanga Kingdom](/Vanga_Kingdom), [Gauda Kingdom](/Gauda_Kingdom), [Samatata](/Samatata), [Pala Empire](/Pala_Empire), and [Jalaluddin Muhammad Shah](/Jalaluddin_Muhammad_Shah)

