Archaeological evidence points to [Neolithic](/Neolithic) settlements scattered across various parts of the region. During the second millennium BCE, communities engaged in rice cultivation were established throughout the area. By the 11th century BCE, inhabitants of Bengal were constructing systematically arranged homes, utilizing copper implements, and crafting distinctive black and red pottery. Remnants of [Copper Age](/Copper_Age) settlements have been unearthed within the region. With the onset of the [Iron Age](/Iron_Age), the people of Bengal adopted iron-based weaponry, tools, and irrigation systems. Commencing around 600 BCE, a second wave of urbanization swept across the northern Indian subcontinent, associated with the [Northern Black Polished Ware](/Northern_Black_Polished_Ware) culture. Significant ancient archaeological sites and cities, including [Dihar](/Dihar_(archaeological_site)), [Pandu Rajar Dhibi](/Pandu_Rajar_Dhibi), [Mahasthangarh](/Mahasthangarh), [Chandraketugarh](/Chandraketugarh), and [Wari-Bateshwar](/Wari-Bateshwar_ruins), emerged during this period. The mighty [Ganges](/Ganges), [Brahmaputra](/Brahmaputra), and [Meghna](/Meghna) rivers served as vital natural conduits for communication and transportation, facilitating movement and trade. The [estuaries](/Estuary) along the [Bay of Bengal](/Bay_of_Bengal) further opened avenues for [maritime](/Maritime_industry) commerce with distant lands in Southeast Asia and beyond.

The ancient geopolitical landscape of Bengal was characterized by divisions such as [Varendra](/Varendra), [Suhma](/Suhma), [Anga](/Anga), [Vanga](/Vanga_Kingdom), [Samatata](/Samatata), and [Harikela]. These regions frequently operated as independent entities or fell under the dominion of larger empires. The Mahasthan [Brahmi](/Brahmi) Inscription provides evidence that Bengal was incorporated into the [Mauryan Empire](/Mauryan_Empire) during the 3rd century BCE. This inscription was an administrative directive, mandating relief measures for a segment of the population experiencing hardship. The discovery of [Punch-marked coins](/Punch-marked_coins) throughout the region indicates the use of coinage as a medium of exchange during the Iron Age. The Vanga Kingdom, from which Bengal derives its name, was renowned for its naval prowess and established overseas colonies. A prince hailing from Bengal, named [Vijaya](/Prince_Vijaya), is credited with founding the first kingdom in [Sri Lanka](/Sri_Lanka). Two of the most influential pan-Indian empires of this era were the Mauryans and the [Gupta Empire](/Gupta_Empire). During this period, Bengal emerged as a significant center for artistic, political, social, spiritual, and scientific innovation, including the conceptualization of [chess](/Chess), the development of [Indian numerals](/Indian_numerals), and the foundational understanding of [zero](/Zero).

The region was known to the ancient [Greeks](/Ancient_Greece) and [Romans](/Roman_world) as [Gangaridai](/Gangaridai). The Greek ambassador [Megasthenes](/Megasthenes) documented its formidable military strength and its dominance over the [Ganges delta](/Ganges_delta). Accounts of the Gangaridai's power reportedly deterred the invasion army of [Alexander the Great](/Alexander_the_Great) in 325 BCE, a force that included formidable [war elephants](/War_elephant) and extensive [cavalry](/Cavalry). Later Roman records attest to established maritime trade routes connecting with Bengal. The discovery of 1st-century Roman coins bearing images of [Hercules](/Hercules) in the region suggests trade links with [Roman Egypt](/Roman_Egypt) via the [Red Sea](/Red_Sea). The [Wari-Bateshwar ruins](/Wari-Bateshwar_ruins) are widely believed to represent the emporium, or trading hub, of Sounagoura, a location mentioned by the Roman geographer [Claudius Ptolemy](/Claudius_Ptolemy). Further evidence of Roman connection comes from a Roman amphora found in the [Purba Medinipur district](/Purba_Medinipur_district) of West Bengal, manufactured in [Aelana](/Aelana) (modern-day Aqaba, [Jordan](/Jordan)) between the 4th and 7th centuries AD.

A Buddhist palm leaf manuscript, dating from the 10th century CE.

The emergence of the first unified Bengali polity is generally attributed to the reign of [Shashanka](/Shashanka). The origins of the [Bengali calendar](/Bengali_calendar) are also traced to his rule. Shashanka established the [Gauda Kingdom](/Gauda_Kingdom). Following Shashanka's demise, Bengal entered a period of internal conflict known as *Matsyanyayam*. The ancient city of [Gauda](/Gauda_(city)) subsequently became the birthplace of the [Pala Empire](/Pala_Empire). Its first emperor, [Gopala I](/Gopala_I), was elected by an assembly of chieftains in Gauda. The Pala kingdom expanded to become one of the most significant empires on the Indian subcontinent. This era witnessed notable advancements in linguistics, sculpture, painting, and education. The empire reached its zenith under [Dharmapala](/Dharmapala_(emperor)) and [Devapala](/Devapala_(Pala_dynasty)). The Palas engaged in a protracted struggle for control of [Kannauj](/Kannauj) with their rivals, the [Gurjara-Pratihara](/Gurjara-Pratihara) and [Rashtrakuta](/Rashtrakuta) dynasties. Pala influence also extended into [Tibet](/Tibet) and [Sumatra](/Sumatra) through the missionary work and travels of [Atisa](/Atisa). The renowned university of [Nalanda](/Nalanda) was established under Pala patronage, as was the [Somapura Mahavihara](/Somapura_Mahavihara), which stood as the largest monastic institution in the subcontinent. The authority of the Palas eventually waned. The [Chandra dynasty](/Chandra_dynasty) exerted control over southeastern Bengal and [Arakan](/Arakan). Concurrently, the [Varman dynasty](/Varman_dynasty) ruled over portions of northeastern Bengal and [Assam](/Assam). By the 11th century, the [Sena dynasty](/Sena_dynasty) had emerged as the primary successor state to the Palas, establishing a resurgent Hindu rule over much of Bengal. The smaller [Deva dynasty](/Deva_dynasty) also held sway in parts of the region. Ancient Chinese travelers, such as [Xuanzang](/Xuanzang), provided detailed accounts of Bengal's cities and its monastic establishments.

Trade between Bengal and the Arab world experienced significant growth following the decline of the [Sasanian Empire](/Sasanian_Empire) and the Arab control of Persian trade routes. Much of this commerce was concentrated in southeastern Bengal, east of the [Meghna River](/Meghna_River). It is plausible that Bengal served as a transit point for early Muslim traders en route to China. Coins from the [Abbasid](/Abbasid) Caliphate have been discovered in the archaeological ruins of [Paharpur](/Somapura_Mahavihara) and [Mainamati]. A collection of Sasanian, [Umayyad](/Umayyad), and Abbasid coins is preserved in the [Bangladesh National Museum](/Bangladesh_National_Museum).

#### Sultanate period

• See also: [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate)

A Chinese manuscript illustrating an African giraffe, a gift from the [Sultan of Bengal](/Sultan_of_Bengal) to China in 1414.

In 1204, the [Ghurid](/Ghurid_Empire) general [Muhammad bin Bakhtiyar Khalji](/Muhammad_bin_Bakhtiyar_Khalji) initiated the Islamic conquest of Bengal. The fall of Lakhnauti, the capital of the Sena dynasty, was documented by historians around 1243. Historical accounts describe Ghurid cavalry rapidly advancing across the Gangetic plains towards Bengal. They reportedly infiltrated the Bengali capital by posing as horse traders. Once within the royal precincts, Bakhtiyar and his men quickly subdued the guards of the Sena king, who had just commenced a meal. The king, along with his retinue, then fled into the forest. The overthrow of the Sena king has been characterized as a coup d'état that "inaugurated an era, lasting over five centuries, during which most of Bengal was dominated by rulers professing the Islamic faith. In itself this was not exceptional, since from about this time until the eighteenth century, Muslim sovereigns ruled over most of the Indian subcontinent. What was exceptional, however, was that among India's interior provinces only in Bengal—a region approximately the size of England and Scotland combined—did a majority of the indigenous population adopt the religion of the ruling class, Islam." Bengal subsequently became a province of the [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate). A coin depicting a horseman, inscribed in both Sanskrit and Arabic, was issued to commemorate the Muslim conquest of Lakhnauti. Bakhtiyar Khalji also led an unsuccessful [Islamic invasion of Tibet](/Islamic_invasion_of_Tibet). For approximately 150 years, Bengal remained under the formal suzerainty of the Delhi Sultanate, though Delhi often struggled to maintain firm control. Rebel governors frequently sought to assert their autonomy or declare independence. Sultan [Iltutmish](/Iltutmish) reasserted control over Bengal in 1225 after quelling rebellions. Due to the considerable overland distance, Delhi's authority in Bengal was often tenuous. Local governors were largely responsible for territorial expansion and consolidating Muslim rule, as exemplified by the [Conquest of Sylhet](/Conquest_of_Sylhet) in 1303.

In 1338, new uprisings erupted in Bengal's three principal towns. Governors in Lakhnauti, [Satgaon](/Satgaon), and [Sonargaon](/Sonargaon) declared their independence from Delhi. This emboldened the ruler of Sonargaon, [Fakhruddin Mubarak Shah](/Fakhruddin_Mubarak_Shah), to annex [Chittagong](/Chittagong) to the Islamic administration. By 1352, [Shamsuddin Ilyas Shah](/Shamsuddin_Ilyas_Shah), the ruler of Satgaon, had successfully unified the region into an independent state, establishing his capital in [Pandua](/Pandua,_Malda). This newly formed breakaway state evolved into the [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate), developing into a formidable territorial, mercantile, and maritime empire that stretched across the eastern reaches of the [Islamic world](/Islamic_world).

Ilyas Shah's initial campaigns saw the first Muslim army penetrate [Nepal](/Nepal) and extend its reach from [Varanasi](/Varanasi) in the west to [Orissa](/Orissa) in the south, and eastward into [Assam](/Assam). The Delhi army continued its efforts to subdue the new Bengali state. The protracted [Bengal-Delhi War](/Bengal_Sultanate-Delhi_Sultanate_War) concluded in 1359 with Delhi formally recognizing Bengal's independence. Ilyas Shah's son, [Sikandar Shah](/Sikandar_Shah), achieved a significant victory by defeating the Delhi Sultan [Firuz Shah Tughluq](/Firuz_Shah_Tughluq) during the Siege of Ekdala Fort. A subsequent peace treaty not only affirmed Bengal's independence but also saw Sikandar Shah presented with a golden crown by the Sultan of Delhi. During the reign of [Ghiyasuddin Azam Shah](/Ghiyasuddin_Azam_Shah), the ruler of [Arakan](/Arakan) sought refuge in Bengal. [Jalaluddin Muhammad Shah](/Jalaluddin_Muhammad_Shah) later assisted the Arakanese king in regaining his throne, in exchange for Arakan becoming a [tributary state](/Tributary_state) of the Bengal Sultanate. Bengali influence in Arakan persisted for three centuries. Bengal also provided assistance to the king of Tripura in reclaiming his throne, again in exchange for tributary status. The ruler of the [Jaunpur Sultanate](/Jaunpur_Sultanate) also found sanctuary in Bengal. Among the [vassal states](/Vassal_state) of Bengal were Arakan, Tripura, [Chandradwip](/Chandradwip), and [Pratapgarh](/Pratapgarh_Kingdom). At its territorial zenith, the Bengal Sultanate encompassed parts of Arakan, Assam, Bihar, Orissa, and Tripura. The sultanate achieved its greatest military triumphs under [Alauddin Hussain Shah](/Alauddin_Hussain_Shah), whose forces, led by [Shah Ismail Ghazi](/Shah_Ismail_Ghazi), overthrew the [Khen dynasty](/Khen_dynasty) and annexed significant portions of Assam, leading to Hussain Shah's proclamation as the conqueror of Assam. In maritime trade, the Bengal Sultanate thrived within the [Indian Ocean trade](/Indian_Ocean_trade) networks, establishing itself as a crucial hub for [re-exports](/Re-export). A giraffe, brought by African envoys from [Malindi](/Malindi) to the Bengal court, was subsequently presented to [Imperial China](/Imperial_China). Ship-owning merchants served as envoys for the Sultan, undertaking journeys to various regions across Asia and Africa. Numerous affluent Bengali merchants resided in Malacca. Bengali vessels carried embassies from [Brunei](/Brunei), [Aceh](/Aceh_Sultanate), and [Malacca](/Malacca_Sultanate) to China. A substantial trade in [shell currency](/Shell_currency) existed between Bengal and the [Maldives](/Maldives). The Sultan of Bengal also contributed funds for the construction of schools in the [Hejaz](/Hejaz) region of Arabia.

The Bengal Sultanate’s history is marked by five dynastic periods: the [Ilyas Shahi dynasty](/Ilyas_Shahi_dynasty), a period of rule by Bengali converts, the [Hussain Shahi dynasty](/Hussain_Shahi_dynasty), a period dominated by Abyssinian usurpers, an interruption by the [Suri dynasty](/Sur_Empire), and concluding with the [Karrani dynasty](/Karrani_dynasty). The [Battle of Raj Mahal](/Battle_of_Raj_Mahal) and the subsequent capture of [Daud Khan Karrani](/Daud_Khan_Karrani) signaled the end of the Bengal Sultanate during the reign of [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) [Akbar](/Akbar). In the late 16th century, a confederation known as the [Baro-Bhuyan](/Baro_Bhuyan), comprising twelve Muslim and Hindu leaders from the [Zamindars of Bengal](/Zamindars_of_Bengal), mounted resistance against Mughal incursions into eastern Bengal. This confederation was led by [Isa Khan](/Isa_Khan), a former prime minister of the Bengal Sultanate. By the 17th century, the Mughals had succeeded in fully integrating the region into their empire.

#### Mughal period

• See also: [Bengal Subah](/Bengal_Subah)

A [Mughal painting](/Mughal_painting) depicting [Emperor Akbar](/Emperor_Akbar) offering prayers following the conquest of Bengal.
Art from [Murshidabad](/Murshidabad). An [ivory](/Ivory) [elephant tusk](/Elephant_tusk) meticulously crafted into a model of the Royal Peacock Barge belonging to the [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal).

[Mughal Bengal](/Mughal_Bengal) was characterized by its exceptionally wealthy elite and stood as the most affluent region within the subcontinent. The prosperity and trade of Bengal so impressed the Mughals that it was described as the "Paradise of the Nations" by the [Mughal Emperors](/Mughal_Emperor). A new provincial capital was established in [Dhaka](/Dhaka). Members of the imperial family were frequently appointed to significant positions within Mughal Bengal, including the crucial role of governor (*[subedar](/Subedar)*). Dhaka consequently became a focal point of imperial intrigue and political maneuvering. Among the most notable governors were the [Rajput](/Rajput) general [Man Singh I](/Man_Singh_I), Prince [Shah Shuja](/Shah_Shuja_(Mughal_prince)), son of Emperor [Shah Jahan](/Shah_Jahan), Prince [Muhammad Azam Shah](/Muhammad_Azam_Shah), son of Emperor [Aurangzeb](/Aurangzeb) and later Mughal emperor, and the influential aristocrat [Shaista Khan](/Shaista_Khan). During Shaista Khan's governorship, the Portuguese and Arakanese were expelled from the strategic port of Chittagong in 1666. Bengal solidified its position as the easternmost frontier of Mughal administration. By the 18th century, Bengal had developed a powerful, semi-independent aristocracy led by the [Nawabs of Bengal](/Nawabs_of_Bengal). The premier minister of Bengal, [Murshid Quli Khan](/Murshid_Quli_Khan), skillfully curtailed the governor's influence, partly due to his past rivalry with Prince Azam Shah. Khan effectively controlled Bengal's finances, holding the position of treasurer. He subsequently relocated the provincial capital from Dhaka to [Murshidabad](/Murshidabad).

In 1717, the Mughal court in Delhi officially recognized the hereditary monarchy of the Nawab of Bengal. The ruler was formally vested with the title of "Nawab of Bengal, [Bihar](/Bihar), and [Orissa](/Orissa)," reflecting his administrative jurisdiction over these three key regions in the eastern subcontinent. The Nawabs commenced issuing their own distinct coinage while maintaining nominal allegiance to the Mughal emperor. The immense wealth generated in Bengal was critically important to the Mughal court, as Delhi derived its most substantial revenue share from the Nawab's treasury. The Nawabs presided over a period of unprecedented economic expansion and prosperity. This era witnessed significant organizational advancements in the textile and banking sectors, the development of a robust military-industrial complex, and the production of exquisite [handicrafts](/Handicrafts) and other valuable commodities. A process of [proto-industrialisation](/Proto-industrialisation) was actively underway. Under the Nawabs' rule, the bustling streets of Bengali cities were filled with brokers, laborers, peons, naibs, wakils, and a diverse array of ordinary traders. The Nawab's state played a crucial role as a major exporter of renowned [Bengal muslin](/Muslin_trade_in_Bengal), silk, [gunpowder](/Gunpowder), and [saltpetre](/Saltpetre). The Nawabs also permitted various European trading companies to establish operations in Bengal, including the [British East India Company](/British_East_India_Company), the [French East India Company](/John_Law%27s_Company), the [Danish East India Company](/Danish_East_India_Company), the [Austrian East India Company](/Austrian_East_India_Company), the [Ostend Company](/Ostend_Company), and the [Dutch East India Company](/Dutch_East_India_Company). Despite this economic interdependence, the Nawabs remained deeply suspicious of the growing influence wielded by these foreign companies.

A Bengali manuscript painting from the 17th century.

Under Mughal suzerainty, Bengal flourished as a central hub for the global [muslin](/Muslin) and silk trades. During the Mughal epoch, Bengal, particularly around its capital city of Dhaka, was the preeminent center for cotton production. This prominence led to muslin being known as "daka" in distant markets, including Central Asia. Domestically, vast regions of India relied on Bengali products such as rice, silks, and cotton textiles. Internationally, European nations depended heavily on Bengali exports, including cotton textiles, silks, and opium. For instance, Bengal accounted for 40% of [Dutch](/Dutch_East_India_Company) imports from Asia, a figure that included over 50% of textiles and approximately 80% of silks. Bengal also served as a significant source of saltpetre for Europe, opium for the Indonesian market, raw silk for Japan and the Netherlands, and cotton and silk textiles for Europe, Indonesia, and Japan. Cotton cloth produced in Bengal found its way to the Americas and across the Indian Ocean. Furthermore, Bengal possessed a substantial [shipbuilding](/Shipbuilding) industry. Economic historian Indrajit Ray estimates that Bengal's annual shipbuilding output during the 16th to 18th centuries reached 223,250 tons, a figure considerably higher than the combined output of nineteen North American colonies between 1769 and 1771.

Following the Portuguese conquests of Malacca and Goa, European traders began navigating the sea routes to Bengal from the 16th century onward. The Portuguese established a [settlement in Chittagong](/Portuguese_Chittagong) with the consent of the Bengal Sultanate in 1528, but were later expelled by the Mughals in 1666. In the 18th century, the Mughal court experienced a rapid disintegration, exacerbated by [Nader Shah's invasion](/Nader_Shah%27s_invasion_of_India) and internal rebellions. This power vacuum allowed European colonial powers to establish trading posts throughout the territory. Ultimately, the British East India Company emerged as the dominant military force in the region, decisively defeating the last independent Nawab of Bengal at the [Battle of Plassey](/Battle_of_Plassey) in 1757.

#### Colonial era (1757–1947)

• Main article: [Bengal Presidency](/Bengal_Presidency)

The [Victoria Memorial](/Victoria_Memorial,_Kolkata) in [Calcutta](/Calcutta).
The [Battle of Plassey](/Battle_of_Plassey) in 1757 marked the commencement of British rule.

The British [East India Company](/East_India_Company) began to exert influence and control over the [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal) starting in 1757, following the pivotal Battle of Plassey. This event signaled the inception of British dominance in India. British control over Bengal steadily increased between 1757 and 1793, during which time the Nawab was progressively reduced to a figurehead. The [Presidency of Fort William](/Presidency_of_Fort_William) gradually consolidated its authority over the entire province of Bengal and its surrounding territories. [Calcutta](/Kolkata) was officially designated as the capital of [British territories in India](/British_territories_in_India) in 1772. The presidency was administered through a combined military and civil structure, which included the [Bengal Army](/Bengal_Army), and boasted the world's sixth earliest operational railway network. For extended periods between 1833 and 1854, the [Governor of Bengal](/Governor_of_Bengal) concurrently held the position of [Governor-General of India](/Governor-General_of_India). Bengal endured several devastating [Bengal famines](/Famines_in_India) during the colonial period, most notably the [Great Bengal famine of 1770](/Great_Bengal_famine_of_1770) and the [Bengal famine of 1943](/Bengal_famine_of_1943). Under British rule, Bengal experienced a significant [deindustrialisation](/Deindustrialisation) of its pre-colonial economy.

The policies enacted by the East India Company led to the decline and deindustrialization of Bengal's once-thriving textile industry. The capital amassed by the Company in Bengal was subsequently reinvested in Great Britain, fueling the burgeoning [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution) in industries such as [textile manufacturing](/Textile_manufacture_during_the_Industrial_Revolution). Economic mismanagement, compounded by drought conditions and a widespread smallpox epidemic, directly precipitated the Great Bengal famine of 1770. This catastrophic event is estimated to have claimed between 1 million and 10 million lives.

In 1862, the [Bengal Legislative Council](/British_Bengal_Legislative_Council) was established, marking the advent of the first modern [legislature in India](/List_of_legislatures_in_South_Asia). The gradual introduction of elected representation occurred during the early 20th century, notably through the [Morley-Minto reforms](/Morley-Minto_reforms) and the implementation of the [dyarchy](/Dyarchy) system. In 1937, the council transitioned to become the upper chamber of the Bengali legislature, while the [Bengal Legislative Assembly](/Bengal_Legislative_Assembly_(1937%E2%80%941947)) was constituted as the lower house. Between 1937 and 1947, the chief executive responsible for the government's administration was the [Prime Minister of Bengal](/Prime_Minister_of_Bengal).

The Bengal Presidency was the largest administrative entity within the [British Empire](/British_Empire). At its peak territorial extent, it encompassed vast swathes of what are now present-day India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Burma, Malaysia, and Singapore. In 1830, the British Straits Settlements, situated along the coast of the [Malacca Straits](/Malacca_Straits), were placed under the residency of Bengal. This territory included the former [Prince of Wales Island](/Prince_of_Wales_Island_(Malaysia)), [Province Wellesley](/Province_Wellesley), [Malacca](/Malacca), and [Singapore](/Singapore). However, in 1867, Penang, Singapore, and Malacca were administratively separated from Bengal to form the [Straits Settlements](/Straits_Settlements). [British Burma](/British_Burma) was incorporated as a province of India before later becoming a [Crown colony](/Crown_colony) in its own right. Western territories, including the [Ceded and Conquered Provinces](/Ceded_and_Conquered_Provinces) and [The Punjab](/Punjab_Province_(British_India)), underwent further reorganization. Northeastern areas were consolidated into [Colonial Assam](/Colonial_Assam).
Traditional [Bengal roofs](/Bengal_roofs) observed in Mughal architecture, circa 1600s.

In 1876, the devastating [Great Backerganj Cyclone of 1876](/1876_Bangladesh_cyclone) struck the [Barisal](/Barisal) region, resulting in the deaths of approximately 200,000 people. Between 1895 and 1920, massive plague outbreaks and famines claimed the lives of an estimated 50 million people in Bengal, predominantly in the western parts of the region.

A wedding observed at night in [Murshidabad](/Murshidabad), Bengal, 1810.
The [Ganges-Brahmaputra delta](/Ganges-Brahmaputra_delta).

The [Indian Rebellion of 1857](/Indian_Rebellion_of_1857) originated on the outskirts of Calcutta, subsequently spreading to Dhaka, Chittagong, Jalpaiguri, Sylhet, and Agartala, in a demonstration of solidarity with the revolts occurring in North India. The suppression of this rebellion led to the dissolution of [Company Rule in India](/Company_Rule_in_India) and the establishment of direct British rule over India, commonly referred to as the [British Raj](/British_Raj). The [Bengal Renaissance](/Bengal_Renaissance), which spanned the late 19th and early 20th centuries, profoundly impacted the cultural and economic landscape of Bengal, ushering in a significant era of advancement in the region's literature and sciences. Between 1905 and 1911, an unsuccessful attempt was made to [divide the province of Bengal](/Partition_of_Bengal_(1905)) into two administrative units: Bengal proper and the short-lived province of [Eastern Bengal and Assam](/Eastern_Bengal_and_Assam). It was within this latter province that the [All India Muslim League](/All_India_Muslim_League) was founded. In 1911, the celebrated Bengali poet and polymath [Rabindranath Tagore](/Rabindranath_Tagore) achieved a historic milestone by becoming the first Asian recipient of the [Nobel Prize in Literature](/Nobel_Prize_in_Literature).

Bengal played a pivotal role in the [Indian independence movement](/Indian_independence_movement), notably through the significant activities of its [revolutionary groups](/Revolutionary_movement_for_Indian_independence). Armed resistance against British rule commenced with the rebellion led by [Titumir](/Titumir) and culminated in the efforts of [Subhas Chandra Bose](/Subhas_Chandra_Bose), who led the [Indian National Army](/Indian_National_Army) in its campaign against the British. Bengal also served as a crucial center for the growing political consciousness among the Muslim population, leading to the establishment of the [All-India Muslim League](/All-India_Muslim_League) in Dhaka in 1906. The movement advocating for a Muslim homeland gained momentum with the [Lahore Resolution](/Lahore_Resolution) in 1943. Concurrently, [Hindu nationalism](/Hindu_nationalism) held considerable sway in Bengal, with prominent organizations like the [Hindu Mahasabha](/Hindu_Mahasabha) being active in the region. Despite a final attempt by political figures such as [Huseyn Shaheed Suhrawardy](/Huseyn_Shaheed_Suhrawardy) and [Sarat Chandra Bose](/Sarat_Chandra_Bose) to establish a [United Bengal](/United_Bengal), the region was ultimately [partitioned](/Partition_of_Bengal_(1947)) along religious lines upon India's [gain of independence](/History_of_the_Republic_of_India) in 1947. The western part was incorporated into India as West Bengal, while the eastern section became a province of Pakistan, initially named [East Bengal](/East_Bengal) and later [East Pakistan](/East_Pakistan), ultimately leading to the formation of Bangladesh in 1971. The partition process was marked by widespread communal violence and significant bloodshed across Bengal.

#### Partition of Bengal (1947)

• See also: [United Bengal](/United_Bengal), [History of Bangladesh](/History_of_Bangladesh), and [History of West Bengal](/History_of_West_Bengal)

• Main article: [Partition of Bengal (1947)](/Partition_of_Bengal_(1947))

On April 27, 1947, the final [Prime Minister of Bengal](/Prime_Minister_of_Bengal), [Huseyn Shaheed Suhrawardy](/Huseyn_Shaheed_Suhrawardy), articulated his vision for an independent Bengal during a press conference in New Delhi. Suhrawardy stated, "Let us pause for a moment to consider what Bengal can be if it remains united. It will be a great country, indeed the richest and the most prosperous in India capable of giving to its people a high standard of living, where a great people will be able to rise to the fullest height of their stature, a land that will truly be plentiful. It will be rich in agriculture, rich in industry and commerce and in course of time it will be one of the powerful and progressive states of the world. If Bengal remains united this will be no dream, no fantasy." On June 2, 1947, British Prime Minister [Clement Attlee](/Clement_Attlee) informed the [US Ambassador to the United Kingdom](/US_Ambassador_to_the_United_Kingdom) of a "distinct possibility Bengal might decide against partition and against joining either Hindustan or Pakistan."

The [Mountbatten Plan](/Mountbatten_Plan), presented on June 3, 1947, outlined the proposed [partition of British India](/Partition_of_British_India). Subsequently, on June 20, the Bengal Legislative Assembly convened to deliberate on the partition of Bengal. In an initial joint session, a decision was reached (by a vote of 126 to 90) that if the province remained united, it should join the [Constituent Assembly of Pakistan](/Constituent_Assembly_of_Pakistan). In a separate meeting of legislators representing [West Bengal](/West_Bengal), the decision was made (58 votes to 21) that the province should be partitioned, with West Bengal aligning with the [Constituent Assembly of India](/Constituent_Assembly_of_India). Concurrently, in a meeting of legislators from [East Bengal](/East_Bengal), it was decided (106 votes to 35) against partitioning the province and (by 107 votes to 34) that East Bengal should join the Constituent Assembly of [Pakistan](/Pakistan) should the partition proceed. On July 6, the [Sylhet district](/Sylhet_Division) of Assam voted in a [referendum to join East Bengal](/1947_Sylhet_referendum).

The task of demarcating the borders of Pakistan and India was assigned to the English barrister [Cyril Radcliffe](/Cyril_Radcliffe). The resulting [Radcliffe Line](/Radcliffe_Line) established the boundary between the [Dominion of India](/Dominion_of_India) and the [Dominion of Pakistan](/Dominion_of_Pakistan), which later evolved into the [Bangladesh-India border](/Bangladesh-India_border). The Radcliffe Line allocated two-thirds of Bengal to the eastern wing of Pakistan. Notably, the historically significant Bengali capitals of [Gaur](/Gauda_(city)), [Pandua](/Pandua,_Malda), [Murshidabad](/Murshidabad), and Calcutta were situated on the Indian side, close to the border with Pakistan. The status of Dhaka as a capital was subsequently reinstated.

### Geography

• Main articles: [Geography of Bangladesh](/Geography_of_Bangladesh) and [Geography of West Bengal](/Geography_of_West_Bengal)

The majority of the Bengal region is situated within the vast [Ganges-Brahmaputra delta](/Ganges-Brahmaputra_delta). However, elevated terrains are present in its northern, northeastern, and southeastern sectors. The Ganges Delta is formed by the confluence of the [Ganges](/Ganges), [Brahmaputra](/Brahmaputra_River), and [Meghna](/Meghna_River) rivers and their numerous tributaries. The total land area of Bengal spans 237,212 square kilometers (91,588 sq mi), with West Bengal covering 88,752 km² (34,267 sq mi) and Bangladesh encompassing 148,460 km² (57,321 sq mi).

The geography of [Bangladesh](/Geography_of_Bangladesh) is predominantly characterized by the expansive and flat Bangladesh Plain. The [Chittagong Hill Tracts](/Chittagong_Hill_Tracts) and the [Sylhet region](/Sylhet_region) are home to most of the [mountains in Bangladesh](/List_of_mountains_in_Bangladesh). A significant portion of Bangladesh lies at an elevation of 10 meters (33 feet) or less above sea level, and it is estimated that approximately 10% of the land would be submerged if the sea level were to rise by 1 meter (3.3 feet). Consequently, much of this region is exceptionally susceptible to seasonal flooding due to the monsoons.
The highest point in Bangladesh is located in the Mowdok range, reaching an elevation of 1,052 meters (3,451 feet). A substantial part of the coastline consists of a [marshy](/Marsh) [jungle], the [Sundarbans](/Sundarbans), which represents the world's largest [mangrove](/Mangrove) forest and harbors a rich diversity of flora and fauna, including the iconic [royal Bengal tiger](/Royal_Bengal_tiger). In 1997, this ecologically sensitive region was designated as endangered.

West Bengal occupies the easternmost part of India, extending from the majestic [Himalayas](/Himalaya) in the north to the Bay of Bengal in the south. The state's total area is 88,752 km² (34,267 sq mi). The [Darjeeling Himalayan hill region](/Darjeeling_Himalayan_hill_region), situated at the northern extremity of the state, is part of the eastern Himalayan range. This area features [Sandakfu](/Sandakfu), which at 3,636 meters (11,929 feet), is the highest peak in the state. The narrow [Terai region](/Terai_region) separates these hills from the plains, which then transition into the Ganges delta towards the south. The [Rarh region](/Rarh_region) lies between the Ganges delta in the east and the [western plateau and high lands](/Western_plateau_and_high_lands). A small coastal strip exists at the extreme south, while the Sundarbans mangrove forests form a striking geographical landmark at the Ganges delta.

At least nine districts in West Bengal and 42 districts in Bangladesh exhibit [arsenic levels in groundwater](/Arsenic_contamination_of_groundwater) that exceed the World Health Organization's maximum permissible limit of 50 μg/L (or 50 parts per billion), rendering the untreated water unfit for human consumption. The consumption of this contaminated water leads to arsenicosis, skin cancer, and a variety of other severe health complications.

#### Geographic distinctions

[Kangchenjunga](/Kangchenjunga), the world's third-highest mountain, as viewed from a tea garden in Bangladesh. Kangchenjunga is frequently visible from the plains of [Tetulia](/Tetulia_Upazila) in the northernmost tip of Bangladesh.

**North Bengal**

The term [North Bengal](/North_Bengal) refers to the northwestern part of Bangladesh and the northern section of West Bengal. The Bangladeshi portion comprises the [Rajshahi Division](/Rajshahi_Division) and [Rangpur Division](/Rangpur_Division). Generally, it encompasses the area situated west of the [Jamuna River](/Jamuna_River_(Bangladesh)) and north of the [Padma River](/Padma_River), including the [Barind Tract](/Barind_Tract). Politically, the West Bengal component includes the [Jalpaiguri Division](/Jalpaiguri_division) and most of the [Malda division](/Malda_division) (excluding the [Murshidabad district](/Murshidabad_district)), along with the [Kishanganj district](/Kishanganj_district) of Bihar. The [Darjeeling](/Darjeeling) Hilly region is also considered part of North Bengal. Residents of Jalpaiguri, Alipurduar, and Cooch Behar typically identify as North Bengali. North Bengal is further subdivided into the [Terai](/Terai) and [Dooars](/Dooars) regions. North Bengal is also recognized for its rich cultural heritage, boasting two UNESCO World Heritage Sites. In addition to the Bengali majority, North Bengal is home to numerous other communities, including Nepalis, [Santhal people](/Santhal_people), Lepchas, and Rajbongshis.

**Northeast Bengal**

The Tanguar Haor in [Sunamganj District](/Sunamganj_District), Bangladesh. *Haors* (wetlands) are a common feature in the Northeast of Bengal.

Northeast Bengal, as per its historical designation, refers to the Sylhet region. This area presently comprises the [Sylhet Division](/Sylhet_Division) of Bangladesh and the [Karimganj district](/Karimganj_district) within the Indian state of [Assam](/Assam). The region is distinguished by its fertile land, numerous rivers, extensive tea plantations, rainforests, and wetlands. The [Brahmaputra](/Brahmaputra_River) and [Barak](/Barak_River) rivers serve as key geographical markers of the area. The city of [Sylhet](/Sylhet) is its principal urban center, and the region is noted for its unique regional dialect, the [Sylheti language](/Sylheti_language). Historically, the region was known by the names Srihatta and Nasratshahi. It was successively ruled by the [Kamarupa](/Kamarupa) and [Harikela](/Harikela) kingdoms, as well as the [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate). Subsequently, it became a district within the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire). Alongside the predominantly Bengali population, the region is inhabited by small communities of [Garo](/Garo_people), [Bishnupriya Manipuri](/Bishnupriya_Manipuri), [Khasi](/Khasi_people), and other tribal minorities. This region represents a significant cultural and geographical crossroads between Bengal and [northeast India](/Northeast_India).

**Central Bengal**

Central Bengal, recognized as one of the most urbanized and developed regions within Bengal, encompasses the [Dhaka Division](/Dhaka_Division) of Bangladesh. It includes the elevated [Madhupur tract](/Madhupur_tract), characterized by a substantial [Sal tree forest](/Sal_(tree)). The Padma River traverses the southern part of the region, delineating the larger [Faridpur](/Faridpur_District) area. To the north lie the greater regions of [Mymensingh](/Mymensingh) and [Tangail](/Tangail).

**South Bengal**

• Main article: [South Bengal](/South_Bengal)

[Cox's Bazar](/Cox%27s_Bazar) boasts the longest uninterrupted sea beach in the world.

South Bengal extends across southwestern Bangladesh and the southern part of the Indian state of West Bengal. The Bangladeshi portion comprises the [Khulna Division](/Khulna_Division), [Barisal Division](/Barisal_Division), and the proposed [Faridpur Division](/Faridpur_Division). The South Bengal section within West Bengal includes the [Presidency division](/Presidency_division), [Burdwan division](/Burdwan_division), and [Medinipur division](/Medinipur_division).

The [Sundarbans](/Sundarbans), a critical [biodiversity hotspot](/Biodiversity_hotspot), is located in South Bengal. Bangladesh contains 60% of this vast mangrove forest, with the remaining portion situated in India.

**Southeast Bengal**

• Main article: [Greater Chittagong](/Greater_Chittagong)

A sunset view at [Potenga Beach](/Patenga), [Chittagong](/Chittagong), Bangladesh.

Southeast Bengal, a region encompassing the hilly and coastal areas of [Chittagong Division](/Chittagong_Division) in southeastern Bangladesh, is characterized by its [Chittagonian](/Chittagonian_language)-speaking and coastal Bengali-speaking populations. This area is historically noted for its [thalassocratic](/Thalassocracy) and [seafaring](/Seafaring) heritage. In antiquity, the region was dominated by the Bengali [Harikela](/Harikela) and [Samatata](/Samatata) kingdoms. By the 9th century, it was known to Arab traders as Samandar. During the medieval period, the region experienced rule under the [Chandra dynasty](/Chandra_dynasty), the [sultanate of Bengal](/Sultanate_of_Bengal), the [kingdom of Tripura](/Kingdom_of_Tripura), the [kingdom of Mrauk U](/Kingdom_of_Mrauk_U), the [Portuguese Empire](/Portuguese_Empire), and the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire), preceding the establishment of British rule. The [Chittagonian language](/Chittagonian_language), closely related to Bengali, is widely spoken in the coastal areas of southeast Bengal. Alongside its Bengali inhabitants, the region is also home to several [Tibeto-Burman](/Tibeto-Burman) ethnic groups, including the [Chakma](/Chakma_people), [Marma](/Marma_people), [Tanchangya](/Tanchangya_people), and [Bawm](/Bawm_people) peoples. Southeast Bengal is considered a vital bridge connecting South Asia to Southeast Asia, with the northern parts of [Arakan](/Arakan) also historically considered within its sphere of influence.

### Places of interest

The region boasts four [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Sites), including the [Sundarbans](/Sundarbans), the [Somapura Mahavihara](/Somapura_Mahavihara), the [Mosque City of Bagerhat](/Mosque_City_of_Bagerhat), and the [Darjeeling Himalayan Railway](/Darjeeling_Himalayan_Railway). Other notable attractions include the temple city of [Bishnupur, Bankura](/Bishnupur,_Bankura), the [Adina Mosque](/Adina_Mosque), the [Caravanserai Mosque](/Katra_Masjid), numerous [zamindar](/Zamindar) palaces (such as [Ahsan Manzil](/Ahsan_Manzil) and [Cooch Behar Palace](/Cooch_Behar_Palace)), the [Lalbagh Fort](/Lalbagh_Fort), the ruins of the [Great Caravanserai](/Bara_Katra), the [Shaista Khan Caravanserai ruins](/Choto_Katra), the [Victoria Memorial, Kolkata](/Victoria_Memorial_(Kolkata)), the Parliament Building of Dhaka, ancient fort cities excavated archaeologically at [Mahasthangarh](/Mahasthangarh), [Mainamati](/Mainamati), [Chandraketugarh](/Chandraketugarh), and [Wari-Bateshwar](/Wari-Bateshwar_ruins), [Jaldapara National Park](/Jaldapara_National_Park), [Lawachara National Park](/Lawachara_National_Park), [Teknaf Game Reserve](/Teknaf_Game_Reserve), and the [Chittagong Hill Tracts](/Chittagong_Hill_Tracts).

[Cox's Bazar](/Cox%27s_Bazar) in southeastern Bangladesh is renowned for hosting the world's longest natural sea beach, extending for an unbroken length of 120 km (75 mi). It is also emerging as a popular destination for [surfing](/Surfing). [St. Martin's Island](/St._Martin%27s_Island), located off the coast of Chittagong Division, is home to Bengal's sole [coral reef](/Coral_reef).

#### Other regions

Present-day [Standard Bengali](/Bengali_language) continues to be spoken in areas beyond Bengal proper, including the Barak Valley, Tripura, and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.

Historically, Bengal was a significant regional power within the Indian subcontinent. The administrative jurisdiction of Bengal historically extended beyond its immediate geographical boundaries. In the 9th century, the Pala Empire, based in Bengal, exerted control over large parts of northern India. The Bengal Sultanate, at various points in its history, governed Bengal, Assam, Arakan, Bihar, and Orissa. During the period of Mughal Bengal, the Nawab of Bengal held authority over Bengal, Bihar, and Orissa. The administrative reach of Bengal achieved its greatest extent under the British Empire, when the Bengal Presidency stretched from the Straits of Malacca in the east to the Khyber Pass in the west. However, in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, administrative reorganizations significantly reduced the territorial scope of Bengal.

Several regions bordering Bengal proper continue to exhibit a substantial level of Bengali cultural influence. The Indian state of Tripura, for instance, has a majority Bengali population. Bengali influence is also prevalent in the Indian regions of Assam, Meghalaya, Bihar, and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, as well as in Myanmar's Rakhine State.

##### Arakan

Bengal and Arakan depicted in 1638.

[Arakan](/Arakan) (now [Rakhine State](/Rakhine_State) in [Myanmar](/Myanmar)) has historically been under significant Bengali cultural influence. Since antiquity, Bengal has played a role in shaping Arakanese culture. The ancient Bengali script was employed in Arakan. [Paul Wheatley](/Paul_Wheatley_(geographer)) described the process of "Indianization" in Arakan. According to [Pamela Gutman], "Arakan was ruled by kings who adopted Indian titles and traditions to suit their own environment. Indian Brahmins conducted royal ceremonies, Buddhist monks spread their teachings, traders came and went and artists and architects used Indian models for inspiration. In the later period, there was also influence from the Islamic courts of Bengal and Delhi." Arakan subsequently emerged as a [vassal state](/Vassal_state) of the [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate). It later evolved into an independent kingdom, with the royal court and culture of the [Kingdom of Mrauk U](/Kingdom_of_Mrauk_U) being heavily influenced by Bengal. [Bengali Muslims](/Bengali_Muslims) served in the royal court as ministers and military commanders. [Bengali Hindus](/Bengali_Hindus) and [Bengali Buddhists](/Bengali_Buddhists) occupied roles as priests. Some of the most significant poets of medieval [Bengali literature](/Bengali_literature), such as [Alaol](/Alaol) and [Daulat Qazi](/Daulat_Qazi), resided in Arakan. In 1660, [Prince Shah Shuja](/Shah_Shuja_(Mughal_prince)), the governor of Mughal Bengal and a claimant to the [Peacock Throne](/Peacock_Throne) of India, sought asylum in Arakan. Bengali influence within the Arakanese royal court persisted until the region's annexation by Burma in the 18th century. The modern-day [Rohingya](/Rohingya_people) population is considered a legacy of Bengal's historical influence on Arakan. Tragically, the [Rohingya genocide](/Rohingya_genocide) led to the displacement of over a million people between 2016 and 2017, with many forced to flee their homes in Rakhine State.

##### Assam

This region forms part of the [Bengali-Assamese languages](/Bengali-Assamese_languages) linguistic area.

The Indian state of [Assam](/Assam) shares numerous cultural affinities with Bengal. The Assamese language utilizes the same script as the Bengali language. The [Barak Valley](/Barak_Valley) is predominantly Bengali-speaking. During the [Partition of India](/Partition_of_India), Assam was partitioned alongside Bengal. The [Sylhet Division](/Sylhet_Division) was incorporated into [East Bengal](/East_Bengal) (Pakistan), with the exception of [Karimganj](/Karimganj), which became part of Indian Assam. Previously, East Bengal and Assam were united as a single province, [Eastern Bengal and Assam](/Eastern_Bengal_and_Assam), from 1905 to 1912 under the [British Raj](/British_Raj). Assam and Bengal were frequently integrated into the same kingdoms, including [Kamarupa](/Kamarupa), [Gauda](/Gauda_Kingdom), and [Kamata](/Kamata_Kingdom). Significant portions of Assam were annexed by [Alauddin Hussain Shah](/Alauddin_Hussain_Shah) during the era of the Bengal Sultanate. Assam was among the few regions on the subcontinent that successfully resisted Mughal expansion and never fully fell under Mughal control.

##### Andaman and Nicobar Islands

Bengali is the most widely spoken language among the inhabitants of the [Andaman and Nicobar Islands](/Andaman_and_Nicobar_Islands), a strategically important archipelago administered by India as a federal territory. These islands were once utilized as a British penal colony. During [World War II](/World_War_II), the islands were occupied by the Japanese and placed under the administration of the [Provisional Government of Free India](/Provisional_Government_of_Free_India). The anti-British leader [Subhash Chandra Bose](/Subhash_Chandra_Bose) visited the islands and renamed them. Between 1949 and 1971, the Indian government resettled a considerable number of [Bengali Hindus](/Bengali_Hindus) in the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.

##### Bihar

Bengal in 1880, encompassing Bihar, Orissa, and Assam.

In antiquity, Bihar and Bengal were frequently part of the same political entities. The ancient region of [Magadha](/Magadha_(Mahajanapada)) encompassed both present-day Bihar and Bengal. Magadha served as the birthplace and stronghold of several pan-Indian empires, including the [Mauryan Empire](/Mauryan_Empire), the [Gupta Empire](/Gupta_Empire), and the [Pala Empire](/Pala_Empire). Under the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire), Bengal, Bihar, and Orissa were administered as a single province. The Nawab of Bengal held the official title of "Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa."

##### Chittagong Hill Tracts

The [Chittagong Hill Tracts](/Chittagong_Hill_Tracts) constitute the southeastern frontier of Bangladesh. Its indigenous population comprises various [Tibeto-Burman](/Tibeto-Burman) ethnicities, including the [Chakma people](/Chakma_people), [Bawm people](/Bawm_people), and [Mru people](/Mru_people), among others. Historically, the region was governed by tribal chieftains presiding over the [Chakma Circle](/Chakma_Circle) and the [Bohmong Circle](/Bohmong_Circle). In 1713, the [Chakma Raja](/Chakma_Raja) entered into a treaty with [Mughal Bengal](/Mughal_Bengal), having obtained permission from [Emperor Farrukhsiyar](/Farrukhsiyar) to engage in trade with the plains districts of Chittagong. Similar to the rulers of Arakan, the Chakma Circle began to adopt Mughal nomenclature and titles. Initially, they resisted the [Permanent Settlement](/Permanent_Settlement) policies and the activities of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company). The tribal royal families of the region came under considerable Bengali cultural influence. Queen [Benita Roy](/Benita_Roy) of the Chakma Circle was a noted friend of [Rabindranath Tagore](/Rabindranath_Tagore). During the colonial period, the region was administered under the [Chittagong Hill Tracts manual]. This manual underwent significant amendments after the end of British rule, and the region was subsequently fully integrated into Bangladesh.

##### Malay Archipelago

The extent of the Bengal Presidency between 1858 and 1867, including the Straits Settlements.

Through extensive trade, settlement, and the exchange of ideas, parts of [Maritime Southeast Asia](/Maritime_Southeast_Asia) became interconnected with Bengal. [115] [116] Influences from Bengal shaped the language, literature, art, governance systems, religions, and philosophies of ancient [Sumatra](/Sumatra) and [Java](/Java). [Hindu-Buddhist kingdoms](/Indianized_kingdom) in Southeast Asia relied on the Bay of Bengal for trade and the dissemination of ideas. The spread of [Islam in Southeast Asia](/Islam_in_Southeast_Asia) also occurred via the Bay of Bengal, which served as a crucial bridge between the Malay Archipelago and the Indo-Islamic states of the Indian subcontinent. [117] [118] A considerable number of affluent merchants from Bengal were based in Malacca. [51] Bengali ships were the largest vessels navigating the waters of the Malay Archipelago during the 15th century. [119]

Between 1830 and 1867, the ports of Singapore and [Malacca](/Malacca), the island of [Penang](/Penang), and a portion of the [Malay Peninsula](/Malay_Peninsula) fell under the administrative jurisdiction of the [Bengal Presidency](/Bengal_Presidency) of the [British Empire](/British_Empire). [120] These territories were collectively known as the [Straits Settlements](/Straits_Settlements). In 1867, the Straits Settlements were administratively separated from the Bengal Presidency and re-established as a [Crown colony](/Crown_colony). [121]

##### Meghalaya

The Indian state of [Meghalaya](/Meghalaya) historically experienced influence from [Shah Jalal](/Shah_Jalal), a Muslim missionary and conqueror originating from [Sylhet](/Sylhet). During the period of [British rule](/British_Raj), the city of [Shillong](/Shillong) served as the [summer capital](/Summer_capital) of [Eastern Bengal and Assam](/Eastern_Bengal_and_Assam) (which comprised modern-day Bangladesh and Northeast India). Shillong notably boasted the highest per capita income in British India. [9]

##### North India

A sepoy of the [Bengal Army](/Bengal_Army), instrumental in the expansion of the Bengal Presidency across the northern reaches of India, extending to the [Khyber Pass](/Khyber_Pass).

The ancient empires of the Mauryan, Gupta, and [Pala](/Pala_Empire) dynasties, centered in the [Magadha](/Magadha_(Mahajanapada)) region (encompassing Bihar and Bengal), extended their influence into northern India. The westernmost boundary of the Bengal Sultanate reached as far as [Varanasi](/Varanasi) and [Jaunpur](/Jaunpur_district). [122] [50] During the 19th century, the [Punjab](/Punjab_Province_(British_India)) and the [Ceded and Conquered Provinces](/Ceded_and_Conquered_Provinces) constituted the westernmost extent of the Bengal Presidency. According to the British historian [Rosie Llewellyn-Jones], "The Bengal Presidency, an administrative division introduced by the East India Company, would later include not only the whole of northern India up to the Khyber Pass on the north-west frontier with Afghanistan, but would spread eastwards to Burma and Singapore as well." [123]

##### Odisha

[Odisha](/Odisha), formerly known as Orissa, has a significant Bengali minority population. Historically, the region has been subjected to invasions originating from Bengal, including a notable invasion by [Shamsuddin Ilyas Shah](/Shamsuddin_Ilyas_Shah). Parts of the region were administered by the [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate) and [Mughal Bengal](/Mughal_Bengal). The [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal) was formally styled as the "Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa," reflecting his granted jurisdiction over Orissa by the [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor). [111]

##### Tibet

During the reign of the [Pala dynasty](/Pala_Empire), Tibet received missionaries from Bengal, whose teachings significantly influenced the development of [Tibetan Buddhism](/Tibetan_Buddhism). [125] [126] One of the most influential missionaries was [Atisa](/Atisa). In the 13th century, Tibet experienced an [Islamic invasion](/Islamic_invasion_of_Tibet) carried out by the forces of [Bakhtiyar Khalji](/Bakhtiyar_Khalji), the Muslim conqueror of Bengal. [127]

##### Tripura

The [princely state of Tripura](/Tripura_(princely_state)) was ruled by the [Manikya dynasty](/Manikya_dynasty) until the [Tripura Merger Agreement](/Tripura_Merger_Agreement) in 1949. Historically, Tripura functioned as a [vassal state](/Vassal_state) of Bengal. Upon ascending the throne with military backing from the Bengal Sultanate in 1464, [Ratna Manikya I](/Ratna_Manikya_I) instituted administrative reforms inspired by the governmental structure of Bengal. The kings of Tripura formally requested Sultan [Barbak Shah](/Ruknuddin_Barbak_Shah) to provide personnel for the development of Tripura's administration. Consequently, [Bengali Hindu](/Bengali_Hindu) bureaucrats, cultivators, and artisans began to settle in Tripura. Today, the Indian state of [Tripura](/Tripura) possesses a majority Bengali population. Modern Tripura serves as a crucial gateway for trade and transportation links connecting [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh) with [Northeast India](/Northeast_India). [129] [130] Within [Bengali culture](/Bengali_culture), the celebrated singer [S. D. Burman](/S._D._Burman) was a member of the Tripura royal family.

### Flora and fauna

The [Bengal tiger](/Bengal_tiger).

The expansive Bengal Plain, which covers the majority of Bangladesh and West Bengal, is recognized as one of the most [fertile](/Soil_fertility) regions on Earth. Its landscape is dominated by lush vegetation and agricultural farmlands. Bengali villages are typically nestled amidst groves of [mango](/Mango), [jackfruit](/Jackfruit), [betel nut](/Betel_nut), and [date palm](/Date_palm). Plantations of rice, [jute](/Jute), [mustard](/Mustard_plant), and [sugarcane](/Sugarcane) are common sights. The numerous [water bodies](/Body_of_water) and [wetlands]() within the Ganges-Brahmaputra delta provide essential habitats for a wide array of aquatic plant life. The northern part of the region features the foothills of the Himalayas (the [Dooars](/Dooars)), characterized by densely wooded [Sal](/Sal_(tree)) and other types of tropical [evergreen](/Evergreen) trees. [131] [132] Above an elevation of 1,000 meters (3,300 ft), the forest transitions into a predominantly subtropical biome, with a prevalence of temperate forest trees such as [oaks](/Oak), [conifers](/Conifer), and [rhododendrons](/Rhododendron). Sal woodlands are also found throughout central Bangladesh, notably within [Bhawal National Park](/Bhawal_National_Park). The [Lawachara National Park](/Lawachara_National_Park) is a significant [rainforest](/Rainforest) located in northeastern Bangladesh. [133] The Chittagong Hill Tracts in southeastern Bangladesh is recognized for its exceptionally high degree of [biodiversity](/Biodiversity). [134]

The [littoral](/Littoral) [Sundarbans](/Sundarbans), situated in the southwestern part of Bengal, is the world's largest [mangrove forest](/Mangrove_forest) and a designated [UNESCO World Heritage Site](/UNESCO_World_Heritage_Site). [135] The region supports an estimated over [89 species of mammals](/List_of_mammals_in_Bangladesh), [628 species of birds](/List_of_birds_of_Bangladesh), and a vast number of [fish species](/List_of_fishes_in_Bangladesh). [136] National symbols for Bangladesh include the [water lily](/Nymphaea), the [oriental magpie-robin](/Oriental_magpie-robin), the [hilsa](/Hilsa) fish, and the [mango tree](/Mango_tree). For West Bengal, the state symbols are the [white-throated kingfisher](/White-throated_kingfisher), the [chatim tree](/Alstonia), and the [night-flowering jasmine](/Night-flowering_jasmine). The [Bengal tiger](/Bengal_tiger) holds the distinction of being the [national animal](/National_animal) of both Bangladesh and India. The [fishing cat](/Fishing_cat) is designated as the state animal of West Bengal.

### Politics

Currently, the core region of Bengal is divided between the [sovereign state](/Sovereign_state) of the [People's Republic of Bangladesh](/Bangladesh) and the [Indian state](/States_and_union_territories_of_India) of [West Bengal](/West_Bengal). [137] The Bengali-speaking [Barak Valley](/Barak_Valley) forms a part of the Indian state of [Assam](/Assam). The Indian state of [Tripura](/Tripura) has a majority Bengali-speaking population and was formerly the princely state of [Hill Tipperah](/Hill_Tipperah). In the Bay of Bengal, [St. Martin's Island](/St._Martin%27s_Island) is administered by Bangladesh, while the [Andaman and Nicobar Islands](/Andaman_and_Nicobar_Islands), which have a plurality of Bengali speakers, are governed by India as a [union territory](/Union_territory).

#### Bangladeshi Republic

• Main article: [Politics of Bangladesh](/Politics_of_Bangladesh)

[Bangabhaban](/Bangabhaban) (the House of Bengal), the [presidential palace](/Presidential_palace) of Bangladesh.

The state of Bangladesh operates as a [parliamentary republic](/Parliamentary_republic), structured around the [Westminster system](/Westminster_system). It possesses a [written constitution](/Constitution_of_Bangladesh) and a [President](/President_of_Bangladesh) elected by the parliament, whose role is largely ceremonial. The [government](/Government_of_Bangladesh) is headed by a Prime Minister, appointed by the President from among the 300 popularly elected Members of Parliament serving in the [Jatiyo Sangshad](/Jatiyo_Sangshad), the national parliament. The Prime Minister is traditionally the leader of the largest single party represented in the Jatiyo Sangshad. The constitution acknowledges [Islam](/Islam) as the country's [established religion](/Established_religion) while simultaneously guaranteeing [freedom of religion](/Freedom_of_religion) for non-Muslims.

Between 1975 and 1990, Bangladesh adopted a [presidential system](/Presidential_system) of governance. Since the 1990s, the country has been administered by non-political technocratic [caretaker governments](/Caretaker_government_of_Bangladesh) on four occasions. The most recent instance occurred under military-backed emergency rule in 2007 and 2008. The [Awami League](/Awami_League) and the [Bangladesh Nationalist Party](/Bangladesh_Nationalist_Party) (BNP) were the two dominant political forces in Bangladesh until the [July Revolution](/July_Revolution_(Bangladesh)) of 2024, which resulted in the ousting of [Sheikh Hasina](/Sheikh_Hasina) following widespread protests and a nationwide uprising. In the aftermath, a non-partisan [interim government](/Yunus_Ministry) was formed under Nobel laureate [Muhammad Yunus](/Muhammad_Yunus) with the mandate to restore democratic governance and implement institutional reforms. Mirroring the functions of the technocratic caretaker governments that operated between 1990 and 2008, this interim administration pledged neutrality and initiated preparations for constitutional amendments and future elections.

Bangladesh is an active member of international organizations including the [UN](/United_Nations), [WTO](/World_Trade_Organization), [IMF](/International_Monetary_Fund), the [World Bank](/World_Bank), [ADB](/Asian_Development_Bank), [OIC](/Organization_of_Islamic_Cooperation), [IDB](/Islamic_Development_Bank), [SAARC](/South_Asian_Association_for_Regional_Cooperation), and [BIMSTEC](/Bay_of_Bengal_Initiative_for_Multi-Sectoral_Technical_and_Economic_Cooperation). Bangladesh has achieved notable progress in [human development](/List_of_countries_by_Human_Development_Index) relative to its neighboring countries.

#### Indian Bengal

• Main article: [Politics of West Bengal](/Politics_of_West_Bengal)

The [Writers' Building](/Writers%27_Building), the official seat of the [Government of West Bengal](/Government_of_West_Bengal).
[Raj Bhavan](/Raj_Bhavan,_Kolkata), the [official residence](/Official_residence) of the [Governor of West Bengal](/Governor_of_West_Bengal), [India](/India).

West Bengal functions as a constituent state within the [Republic of India](/India), possessing its own local [executives](/State_governments_of_India) and [assemblies](/Vidhan_Sabha), features common to all states in the Indian federal system. The [president of India](/President_of_India) appoints a governor to serve as the ceremonial representative of the [union government](/Government_of_India). The governor, in turn, appoints the [chief minister](/Chief_minister) based on the nomination of the legislative assembly. The chief minister is traditionally the leader of the party or coalition holding the majority of seats in the assembly. [President's rule](/President%27s_rule) is frequently invoked in Indian states, representing a direct intervention by the union government led by the [prime minister of India](/Prime_minister_of_India). The Bengali-speaking region of India contributes 48 seats to the lower house of the Indian Parliament, the [Lok Sabha](/Lok_Sabha).

Each state elects representatives to the Indian lower house of parliament, the [Lok Sabha](/Lok_Sabha). Furthermore, each state nominates members to the Indian upper house of parliament, the [Rajya Sabha](/Rajya_Sabha).

State legislative assemblies also play a significant role in the election of the ceremonial president of India. The former president of India, [Pranab Mukherjee](/Pranab_Mukherjee), hailed from West Bengal and was a prominent leader of the [Indian National Congress](/Indian_National_Congress). The former [leader of opposition](/Leader_of_Opposition_in_Lok_Sabha) in India, [Adhir Ranjan Chowdhury](/Adhir_Ranjan_Chowdhury), represents [West Bengal](/West_Bengal), having been elected from the [Baharampur Lok Sabha constituency](/Baharampur_Lok_Sabha_constituency).

The principal political forces within the Bengali-speaking region of India include the [Left Front](/Left_Front_(West_Bengal)) and the [Trinamool Congress](/Trinamool_Congress), alongside the [Indian National Congress](/Indian_National_Congress) and the [Bharatiya Janata Party](/Bharatiya_Janata_Party). The Bengali-speaking zone of India has historically been considered a stronghold for [Communism in India](/Communism_in_India). While traditionally Bengalis have not voted strictly along communal lines, this perception has seen shifts in recent years. The [Trinamool Congress](/Trinamool_Congress), based in [West Bengal](/West_Bengal), is currently the third-largest party in India in terms of the number of Members of Parliament (MPs) and Members of the Legislative Assembly (MLAs), following the [Bharatiya Janata Party](/Bharatiya_Janata_Party) and the [Indian National Congress](/Indian_National_Congress). Previously, the [Communist Party of India (Marxist)](/Communist_Party_of_India_(Marxist)) held this position.

#### Crossborder relations

• Main articles: [Bangladesh-India relations](/Bangladesh-India_relations), [Indians in Bangladesh](/Indians_in_Bangladesh), and [Bangladeshis in India](/Bangladeshis_in_India)

A meeting between naval commanders from India and Bangladesh.

India and Bangladesh rank as the world's most populous and eighth most populous countries, respectively. [Bangladesh-India relations](/Bangladesh-India_relations) commenced on a positive note in 1971, with India playing a crucial role in the [liberation of Bangladesh](/Liberation_of_Bangladesh). The Indian Bengali population and media provided substantial support to the independence movement in the former East Pakistan. The two nations shared a twenty-five-year friendship treaty between 1972 and 1996. However, disagreements concerning river water sharing, border security, and trade access have persistently strained the relationship. In more recent years, a consensus has emerged in both countries regarding the significance of fostering strong bilateral relations and developing a strategic partnership in South Asia and beyond. Commercial, cultural, and defense cooperation have seen expansion since 2010, when Prime Ministers [Sheikh Hasina](/Sheikh_Hasina) and [Manmohan Singh](/Manmohan_Singh) pledged to revitalize ties.

The High Commission of Bangladesh in New Delhi operates a Deputy High Commission in [Kolkata](/Kolkata) and a consular office in [Agartala](/Agartala). India maintains a High Commission in [Dhaka](/Dhaka), with consulates located in [Chittagong](/Chittagong) and [Rajshahi](/Rajshahi). Frequent international air, bus, and rail services connect major cities in Bangladesh and Indian Bengal, particularly the three largest urban centers: Dhaka, Kolkata, and Chittagong. The contentious issue of undocumented immigration of Bangladeshi workers, often highlighted by right-wing nationalist parties in India, garners limited sympathy in West Bengal. [139] India has since implemented border fencing, a measure that has drawn criticism from Bangladesh. [140]

### Economy

• Main articles: [Economy of Bangladesh](/Economy_of_Bangladesh) and [Economy of West Bengal](/Economy_of_West_Bengal)

The cityscape of downtown [Dhaka](/Dhaka).

The [Ganges Delta](/Ganges_Delta) provided distinct advantages, including fertile soil, abundant water resources, and a rich supply of fish, wildlife, and fruits. [141] Living standards for Bengal's elite were comparatively higher than in other regions of the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent). [141] Between 400 and 1200 CE, Bengal exhibited a well-developed economy characterized by structured land ownership, flourishing agriculture, livestock management, efficient shipping, robust trade and commerce, effective taxation systems, and a sophisticated banking sector. [142] The apparent economic vitality of Bengal in the early 15th century is attributed to the cessation of tribute payments to the [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate) following the establishment of the [Bengal Sultanate], which halted the outflow of wealth. The travelogue of [Ma Huan](/Ma_Huan) documented a thriving shipbuilding industry and significant [international trade](/International_trade) within Bengal.

In 1338, [Ibn Battuta](/Ibn_Battuta) observed that the silver *taka* was the predominant currency in the region, eclipsing the Islamic [dinar](/Dinar). [143] By 1415, members of [Admiral Zheng He](/Admiral_Zheng_He)'s expedition also noted the widespread use and importance of the *taka*. This currency served as a crucial symbol of sovereignty for the [Sultan of Bengal](/Sultan_of_Bengal). The Sultanate of Bengal established an estimated 27 [mints](/Mint_(facility)) across its provincial capitals, which were recognized as Mint Towns and played an integral role in the governance and administration of Bengal.

The *taka* continued to be issued in [Mughal Bengal](/Mughal_Bengal), which inherited the legacy of the sultanate. As Bengal's prosperity grew and its integration into the [world economy](/World_economy) deepened under Mughal rule, the *taka* gradually replaced shell currency in rural areas, becoming the standardized [legal tender](/Legal_tender). It was also utilized in commercial transactions with entities such as the [Dutch East India Company](/Dutch_East_India_Company), the [French East India Company](/John_Law%27s_Company), the [Danish East India Company](/Danish_East_India_Company), and the [British East India Company](/British_East_India_Company). Under Mughal administration, Bengal emerged as the epicenter of the global [muslin](/Muslin) trade. The patronage of the Mughal imperial court significantly bolstered the [muslin trade in Bengal](/Muslin_trade_in_Bengal). Muslin originating from Bengal was highly prized and worn by aristocratic women in courts as far afield as Europe, Persia, and Central Asia. The treasury of the [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal) represented the most substantial source of revenue for the imperial Mughal court in Delhi. Bengal possessed a highly developed [shipbuilding](/Shipbuilding) sector. The annual shipbuilding output of Bengal during the 16th and 17th centuries was estimated at 223,250 tons, exceeding the volume of shipbuilding in the nineteen colonies of North America between 1769 and 1771. [61]

Historically, Bengal has been recognized as the industrial vanguard of the subcontinent. Mughal Bengal witnessed the emergence of a proto-industrial economy, underpinned by its thriving textile and gunpowder industries. This organized, early modern economy experienced a period of flourishing until the mid-18th century, marking the beginning of British rule. During this transformative period, the region underwent radical and revolutionary changes in its governmental structures, trade practices, and regulatory frameworks. The British displaced the indigenous ruling elite and facilitated the transfer of a significant portion of the region's wealth back to the colonial metropole in Britain. Throughout much of the colonial era, the Bengali economy was primarily geared towards the trade of raw materials, with a particular emphasis on the [jute trade](/Jute_trade).

The [partition of India](/Partition_of_India) profoundly altered the economic geography of the region. Calcutta, located in West Bengal, inherited a robust industrial base from the colonial period, especially in jute processing. East Pakistan subsequently developed its own industrial infrastructure, including the establishment of the [world's largest jute mill](/Adamjee_Jute_Mills). In 1972, the newly independent government of Bangladesh initiated a policy of nationalizing 580 industrial plants. These industries were later privatized in the late 1970s as Bangladesh transitioned towards a market-oriented economy. The implementation of [liberal reforms](/Economic_liberalization) in 1991 catalyzed a significant expansion of Bangladesh's private sector, encompassing industries such as telecommunications, natural gas, textiles, pharmaceuticals, ceramics, steel, and shipbuilding. As of 2022, Bangladesh held the position of the second-largest economy in South Asia, following India. [148] [149]

The region is a global leader in rice production, with West Bengal being India's largest rice producer and Bangladesh ranking as the world's fourth-largest rice producer. [150] Three Bengali economists have been honored with Nobel Prizes: [Amartya Sen](/Amartya_Sen) and [Abhijit Banerjee], who received the [Nobel Memorial Prize in Economics](/Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economics), and [Muhammad Yunus](/Muhammad_Yunus), who was awarded the [Nobel Peace Prize](/Nobel_Peace_Prize).

