In addition, several minority ethnolinguistic groups are indigenous to the region. These encompass speakers of other Indo-Aryan languages (e.g., [Bishnupriya Manipuri](/Bishnupriya_Manipuri_language), [Oraon Sadri](/Sadri_language), various [Bihari languages](/Bihari_languages)), [Tibeto-Burman languages](/Tibeto-Burman_languages) (e.g., [A'Tong](/A%27Tong_language), [Chak](/Chak_language), [Koch](/Koch_language), [Garo](/Garo_language), [Megam](/Megam_language), [Meitei](/Meitei_language) (officially referred to as "[Manipuri](/Manipuri_language)"), [Mizo](/Mizo_language), [Mru](/Mru_language), [Pangkhua](/Pangkhua_language), [Rakhine](/Rakhine_language)/[Marma](/Marma_Language), [Kok Borok](/Kok_Borok_language), [Riang](/Reang_language), [Tippera](/Tippera_language), [Usoi](/Usoi_language), various [Chin languages](/Chin_languages)), [Austroasiatic languages](/Austroasiatic_languages) (e.g., [Khasi](/Khasi_language), [Koda](/Koda_language), [Mundari](/Mundari_language), [Pnar](/Pnar_language), [Santali](/Santali_language), [War](/War_language)), and [Dravidian languages](/Dravidian_languages) (e.g., [Kurukh](/Kurukh_language), [Sauria Paharia](/Sauria_Paharia_language)). [157]

Life expectancy stands at approximately 72.49 years for Bangladesh [162] and 70.2 years for West Bengal. [163] [164] In terms of literacy, West Bengal leads with a literacy rate of 77%, [155] while in Bangladesh, the rate is approximately 72.9%. [165] [c] The poverty rate in West Bengal is recorded at 19.98%, whereas in Bangladesh, it stands at 12.9%. [166] [167] [168]

West Bengal exhibits one of the lowest total fertility rates (TFR) in India. West Bengal's TFR of 1.6 is comparable to that of Canada. [169]

