Other significant cities within the West Bengal region include [Howrah](/Howrah), [Kalyani, West Bengal](/Kalyani,_West_Bengal), [Basirhat](/Basirhat), [Kharagpur](/Kharagpur), [Durgapur](/Durgapur), [Coochbehar](/Coochbehar), [Malda, West Bengal](/Malda,_West_Bengal), [Chandannagar](/Chandannagar), [Bardhaman](/Bardhaman), and [Darjeeling](/Darjeeling), among others. [175]

##### Other major cities in Bangladesh

Key cities in Bangladesh include [Sylhet](/Sylhet), [Khulna](/Khulna), [Jessore](/Jessore), [Rajshahi](/Rajshahi), [Rangpur, Bangladesh](/Rangpur,_Bangladesh), and [Cox's Bazar](/Cox%27s_Bazar).

### Culture

• Main article: [Culture of Bengal](/Culture_of_Bengal)

#### Language

• Main article: [Bengali language](/Bengali_language)

[Bengali Letters](/Bengali_alphabet).

The [Bengali language](/Bengali_language) evolved between the 7th and 10th centuries CE from [Apabhraṃśa](/Apabhra%E1%B9%83%C5%9Ba) and [Magadhi Prakrit](/Magadhi_Prakrit). [176] It is written using the indigenous [Bengali alphabet](/Bengali_alphabet), which is a descendant of the ancient [Brahmi script](/Brahmi_script). Bengali ranks as the 5th most spoken language globally by native speakers. It belongs to the eastern [Indo-Aryan language](/Indo-Aryan_language) group and represents one of the easternmost branches of the [Indo-European language family](/Indo-European_language_family). It is part of the broader [Bengali-Assamese languages](/Bengali-Assamese_languages) cluster. Bengali has exerted a significant influence on other languages in the region, including [Odia](/Odia_language), [Assamese](/Assamese_language), [Chakma](/Chakma_language), [Nepali](/Nepali_language), and [Rohingya](/Rohingya_language). It holds the status of the sole [state language](/State_language) of Bangladesh and is the second most spoken language in India. [177] Globally, it ranks as the seventh most spoken language by total number of speakers.

Bengali serves as a unifying linguistic force within a culturally diverse region and plays a crucial role in fostering regional identity. The [Bengali language movement](/Bengali_language_movement) of 1952 in East Pakistan is commemorated by [UNESCO](/UNESCO) as [International Mother Language Day](/International_Mother_Language_Day), underscoring global efforts to preserve linguistic heritage.

#### Currency

• Main article: [History of the taka](/History_of_the_taka)

A silver coin featuring Proto-Bengali script, dating from the 9th century.

In both [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh) and [West Bengal](/West_Bengal), currency is commonly referred to as *taka*. The [Bangladesh taka](/Bangladesh_taka) officially upholds this tradition, while the [Indian rupee](/Indian_rupee) is also inscribed as *taka* in Bengali script on all its banknotes. The [history of the taka](/History_of_the_taka) extends back centuries. Bengal was home to one of the world's earliest coin currencies during the first millennium BCE. Under the Delhi Sultanate, the *taka* was introduced by [Muhammad bin Tughluq](/Muhammad_bin_Tughluq) in 1329. Bengal became a stronghold for the *taka*, with the silver currency serving as a critical symbol of sovereignty for the [Sultanate of Bengal](/Sultanate_of_Bengal). It was traded along the [Silk Road](/Silk_Road) and its influence extended to replication in [Nepal](/Nepal) and China's [Tibetan](/Tibet) protectorate. The [Pakistani rupee](/Pakistani_rupee) featured Bengali script spelling *taka* on its banknotes until the creation of Bangladesh in 1971.

#### Literature

• Main articles: [Bengali literature](/Bengali_literature) and [Bangladeshi English literature](/Bangladeshi_English_literature)

[Rabindranath Tagore](/Rabindranath_Tagore), often referred to as the Bengali Shakespeare, being honored at the Parliament of [Iran](/Iran) in the 1930s.

Bengali literature boasts a rich and extensive heritage. Its history traces back to the 3rd century BCE, when [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit) was the predominant language, written in the [Brahmi](/Brahmi) script. The [Bengali language](/Bengali_language) and its [script](/Bengali%E2%80%93Assamese_script) evolved around 1000 CE from [Magadhi Prakrit](/Magadhi_Prakrit). Bengal possesses a long-standing tradition in folk literature, evidenced by works such as the [Chôrjapôdô](/Charyapada), [Mangalkavya](/Mangalkavya), [Shreekrishna Kirtana](/Shreekrishna_Kirtana), [Maimansingha Gitika], and [Thakurmar Jhuli]. Bengali literature during the medieval period was often either religious in nature (e.g., the works of [Chandidas](/Chandidas)) or adaptations from other languages (e.g., the writings of [Alaol](/Alaol)). The [Bengal Renaissance](/Bengal_Renaissance) in the 19th and 20th centuries saw the modernization of [Bengali literature] through the contributions of authors like [Michael Madhusudan Dutta](/Michael_Madhusudan_Dutta), [Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar](/Ishwar_Chandra_Vidyasagar), [Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay](/Bankim_Chandra_Chattopadhyay), [Rabindranath Tagore](/Rabindranath_Tagore), [Sarat Chandra Chattopadhyay](/Sarat_Chandra_Chattopadhyay), [Kazi Nazrul Islam](/Kazi_Nazrul_Islam), [Satyendranath Dutta](/Satyendranath_Dutta), [Begum Rokeya](/Begum_Rokeya), and [Jibanananda Das](/Jibanananda_Das). Prominent Bengali writers of the 20th century include [Syed Mujtaba Ali](/Syed_Mujtaba_Ali), [Jasimuddin](/Jasimuddin), [Manik Bandopadhyay](/Manik_Bandopadhyay), [Tarasankar Bandyopadhyay](/Tarasankar_Bandyopadhyay), [Bibhutibhushan Bandyopadhyay](/Bibhutibhushan_Bandyopadhyay), [Buddhadeb Bose](/Buddhadeb_Bose), [Sunil Gangopadhyay](/Sunil_Gangopadhyay), and [Humayun Ahmed](/Humayun_Ahmed).

Distinguished contemporary Bengali writers working in English include [Amitav Ghosh](/Amitav_Ghosh), [Tahmima Anam](/Tahmima_Anam), [Jhumpa Lahiri](/Jhumpa_Lahiri), and [Zia Haider Rahman], among others.

#### Personification

• Main article: [Mother Bengal](/Mother_Bengal)

The [Bangamata](/Bangamata), a female [personification](/National_personification) of Bengal, emerged during the [Bengali Renaissance](/Bengali_Renaissance) and was later adopted by [Bengali nationalists](/Bengali_nationalism). [Hindu nationalists](/Hindu_nationalism) adopted a modified version, [Bharat Mata](/Bharat_Mata), as a national personification of India. [179] Mother Bengal symbolizes not only biological motherhood but also its associated characteristics: protection, unending love, solace, care, and the origin and end of life. In [Amar Sonar Bangla], the national anthem of Bangladesh, [Rabindranath Tagore](/Rabindranath_Tagore) repeatedly uses the word "Maa" (Mother) to refer to the motherland, Bengal.

The nationalist sentiments evoked by the painting transformed [Abanindranath Tagore](/Abanindranath_Tagore)'s initial concept of "[Bangamata](/Bangamata)" after the [Partition of Bengal (1905)](/Partition_of_Bengal_(1905)) into "[Bharat Mata](/Bharat_Mata)" (Mother India), a pan-Indian figure that inspired people across the nation during the [Indian independence movement](/Indian_independence_movement).

A monument commemorating [Mother Language Day](/Mother_Language_Day) in [Kolkata](/Kolkata), [West Bengal](/West_Bengal), depicting the Language Martyrs cradled by [Bangamata](/Bangamata) (Mother Bengal) during the [Bangladesh Liberation War](/Bangladesh_Liberation_War).

#### Art

• See also: [Bangladeshi art](/Bangladeshi_art)

Paintings by Bangladeshi artists on display at an art gallery in Dhaka.

The Pala-Sena School of Art, which flourished in Bengal between the 8th and 12th centuries, is regarded as a pinnacle of classical Asian art, encompassing both sculptures and paintings. [180] [181] [182]

Islamic Bengal was renowned for its production of exquisite cotton fabrics and [saris](/Sari), particularly the [Jamdani](/Jamdani), which received royal patronage from the Mughal court. [183] The [Bengal School](/Bengal_School_of_Art) of painting gained prominence in [Kolkata](/Kolkata) and [Shantiniketan](/Shantiniketan) during the [British Raj](/British_Raj) in the early 20th century. Its practitioners were among the pioneers of modern painting in India. [184] [Zainul Abedin](/Zainul_Abedin) is recognized as the pioneer of modern [Bangladeshi art](/Bangladeshi_art). The country currently boasts a dynamic and internationally acclaimed [contemporary art](/Contemporary_art) scene. [185]

#### Architecture

• Main article: [Architecture of Bengal](/Architecture_of_Bengal)

[Bungalows](/Bungalow) originated from [Bengali architecture](/Bengali_architecture).

Classical Bengali architecture is distinguished by its [terracotta](/Terracotta) structures. The ancient kingdoms of Bengal laid the groundwork for the region's architectural heritage through the construction of monasteries and temples, such as the [Somapura Mahavihara](/Somapura_Mahavihara). During the [sultanate period](/Bengal_Sultanate), a unique and magnificent style of Islamic architecture developed in the region. [186] Many of these Islamic structures were relatively small, artistically crafted terracotta mosques characterized by multiple domes and the absence of minarets. Bengal was also home to the largest mosque in South Asia, located at [Adina](/Adina_Mosque). Bengali vernacular architecture is credited with inspiring the widespread popularity of the [bungalow](/Bungalow). [187]

The Bengal region also possesses a rich legacy of [Indo-Saracenic architecture](/Indo-Saracenic_architecture), evident in numerous [zamindar](/Zamindar) palaces and mansions. The [Victoria Memorial, Kolkata](/Victoria_Memorial,_Kolkata) stands as a prime example of this architectural style.

In the 1950s, [Muzharul Islam](/Muzharul_Islam) spearheaded the modernist terracotta architectural style in South Asia. This movement culminated in the design of the [Jatiyo Sangshad Bhaban](/Jatiyo_Sangshad_Bhaban) by the acclaimed American architect [Louis Kahn](/Louis_Kahn) in the 1960s. Kahn's design drew inspiration from the aesthetic heritage and geographical characteristics of Bengali architecture. [188] [189]

#### Sciences

• Main article: [Science and technology in Bangladesh](/Science_and_technology_in_Bangladesh)

A sculpture of the Bengali-American engineer [Fazlur Rahman Khan](/Fazlur_Rahman_Khan) displayed at the [Sears Tower](/Sears_Tower) in the United States.

The [Gupta dynasty](/Gupta_dynasty), believed to have originated in North Bengal, is credited with pioneering the invention of [chess](/Chess), conceptualizing [zero](/Zero), formulating the [theory of Earth orbiting the Sun](/Heliocentrism), advancing the study of [solar](/Sun) and [lunar](/Moon) eclipses, and fostering the flourishing of [Sanskrit literature](/Sanskrit_literature) and [drama](/Sanskrit_drama). [34] [190]

The educational reforms implemented during the [British Raj](/British_Raj) fostered the emergence of numerous distinguished scientists from Bengal. Sir [Jagadish Chandra Bose](/Jagadish_Chandra_Bose) pioneered research in radio and [microwave](/Microwave) [optics](/Optics), made significant contributions to [plant science](/Plant_science), and laid the foundational principles for experimental science in the Indian subcontinent. [191] The [IEEE](/IEEE) recognized him as one of the [fathers](/People_known_as_the_father_or_mother_of_something) of radio science. [192] He was the first individual from the Indian subcontinent to be granted a [US patent](/United_States_patent_law) in 1904. Between 1924 and 1925, while conducting research at the University of Dhaka, [Satyendra Nath Bose](/Satyendra_Nath_Bose), renowned for his work in [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics), established the theoretical basis for [Bose–Einstein statistics](/Bose%E2%80%93Einstein_statistics) and the concept of the [Bose–Einstein condensate](/Bose%E2%80%93Einstein_condensate). [193] [194] [195] [Meghnad Saha] was the first scientist to establish a correlation between a star's spectrum and its temperature, developing thermal ionization equations (notably the [Saha ionization equation](/Saha_ionization_equation)) that have become fundamental in astrophysics and astrochemistry. [196] [Amal Kumar Raychaudhuri] was a physicist recognized for his research in general relativity and cosmology. His most significant contribution is the eponymous [Raychaudhuri equation](/Raychaudhuri_equation), which demonstrates the inevitable emergence of singularities in general relativity and is a crucial element in the proofs of the Penrose–Hawking singularity theorems. [197]

In the United States, the Bangladeshi-American engineer [Fazlur Rahman Khan](/Fazlur_Rahman_Khan) gained recognition as the "father of tubular designs" in skyscraper construction. [Ashoke Sen] is an Indian theoretical physicist whose primary research area is string theory. He was among the initial recipients of the [Fundamental Physics Prize](/Fundamental_Physics_Prize) "for opening the path to the realization that all string theories are different limits of the same underlying theory." [198]

#### Music

• Main articles: [Music of Bengal](/Music_of_Bengal) and [Music of Bangladesh](/Music_of_Bangladesh)

A [Baul](/Baul) musician. The Baul ballads of Bangladesh are recognized by UNESCO as part of humanity's [intangible cultural heritage](/Intangible_cultural_heritage).

The [Baul](/Baul) tradition represents a unique heritage of Bengali folk music. [199] The 19th-century mystic poet [Lalon Shah](/Lalon_Shah) is celebrated as the most esteemed practitioner of this tradition. [200] Other forms of folk music include [Gombhira](/Gombhira), [Bhatiali](/Bhatiali), and [Bhawaiya](/Bhawaiya). [Hason Raja](/Hason_Raja) is a distinguished folk poet from the Sylhet region. Folk music in Bengal is often accompanied by the [ektara], a one-stringed instrument. Additional instruments commonly used include the [dotara](/Dotara), [dhol](/Dhol), flute, and [tabla](/Tabla). The region also boasts a rich heritage in [North Indian classical music](/Hindustani_classical_music).

#### Cuisine

• Main articles: [Bengali cuisine](/Bengali_cuisine) and [Bangladeshi cuisine](/Bangladeshi_cuisine)

[Bengali cuisine](/Bengali_cuisine) is distinguished as the only traditionally developed multi-course culinary tradition originating from the Indian subcontinent. Rice and fish are considered traditional staple foods, leading to the popular saying, "fish and rice make a Bengali." [201] Bengal's extensive array of fish-based dishes includes preparations of [Hilsa](/Hilsa), a particularly favored fish among Bengalis. Bengalis are also renowned for their distinctive milk-based [sweetmeats](/Confectionery), such as [Rôshogolla](/Rasgulla), Chômchôm, and various types of [Pithe](/Pithe). The historic city of Dhaka is celebrated for its unique Indo-Islamic cuisine, featuring dishes like [biryani](/Biryani), [bakarkhani](/Bakarkhani), and [kebab](/Kebab).

#### Boats

• See also: [Country boats in Bangladesh](/Country_boats_in_Bangladesh)

An 18th-century painting depicting a [budgerow].

Approximately 150 distinct types of Bengali country boats navigate the [700 rivers of the Bengal delta](/List_of_rivers_in_Bangladesh), the extensive [floodplain](/Floodplain), and numerous [oxbow lakes](/Oxbow_lake). These boats vary significantly in design and size, including models like the [dinghy](/Dinghy) and [sampan](/Sampan), among others. Country boats are an integral element of [Bengali culture](/Bengali_culture) and have served as inspiration for generations of artists and poets, including the ivory artisans of the Mughal era. The region possesses a long-standing shipbuilding tradition, dating back many centuries. Wooden boats are constructed from timber such as Jarul ([Dipterocarpus turbinatus]), Sal ([Shorea robusta]), Sundari ([Heritiera fomes]), and [Burma teak](). Medieval Bengal was a significant shipbuilding hub for the naval forces of the [Mughal](/Mughal_Empire) and [Ottoman](/Ottoman_Empire) empires. [202] [203] In the 19th century, the British [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) also utilized Bengali shipyards, including for the construction of vessels involved in the [Battle of Trafalgar](/Battle_of_Trafalgar).

#### Attire

A traditional bride from Bangladesh.

Bengali women commonly wear the [shaŗi](/Sari), often featuring designs distinct to local cultural customs. In urban settings, Western-style attire is frequently worn by both women and men. European-style clothing has greater acceptance among men. Men also wear traditional garments such as the *panjabi* [204] paired with a [dhoti](/Dhoti) or [pyjama](/Pyjama), often for religious occasions. The [lungi](/Lungi), a type of sarong-like garment, is widely worn by Bangladeshi men. [ [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) ]

#### Festivals

• Main articles: [List of festivals in Bangladesh](/List_of_festivals_in_Bangladesh) and [List of festivals in West Bengal](/List_of_festivals_in_West_Bengal)

A [Mangal Shobhajatra](/Mangal_Shobhajatra) parade during the [Bengali New Year](/Bengali_New_Year) in Bangladesh.

For [Bengali Muslims](/Bengali_Muslims), the primary religious festivals include [Eid al-Fitr](/Eid_al-Fitr), [Eid al-Adha](/Eid_al-Adha), [Mawlid](/Mawlid), [Muharram](/Muharram), and [Shab-e-Barat](/Barat_Night). For [Bengali Hindus](/Bengali_Hindus), major religious celebrations encompass [Durga Puja](/Durga_Puja), [Kali Puja](/Kali_Puja), [Janmashtami](/Janmashtami), and [Rath Yatra](/Rath_Yatra). In honor of [Bengali Buddhists](/Bengali_Buddhists) and [Bengali Christians](/Bengali_Christians), both [Buddha's Birthday](/Buddha%27s_Birthday) and [Christmas](/Christmas) are observed as public holidays throughout the region. The [Bengali New Year](/Bengali_New_Year) stands as the principal secular festival of Bengali culture, celebrated by people irrespective of their religious and social backgrounds. The largest congregation in Bengal is the [Bishwa ijtema](/Bishwa_ijtema), which also ranks as the world's second-largest Islamic congregation. Other significant Bengali festivals include the celebration of the [first day of spring](/Pohela_Falgun) and the [Nabanna](/Nabanna) harvest festival held in autumn.

#### Media

• See also: [Mass media in Bangladesh](/Mass_media_in_Bangladesh)

Bangladesh possesses a diverse, outspoken, and predominantly privately owned [press](/News_media). English-language publications are popular among the urban readership. [205] In 2005, West Bengal hosted 559 published newspapers, [206] of which 430 were in Bengali. The region is home to the largest circulated [Bengali language newspapers](/Bengali-language_newspapers) and magazines globally. [206] [Bengali cinema](/Cinema_of_Bangladesh) is primarily centered around the media hubs of Dhaka and Kolkata.

#### Sports

• See also: [Bangladesh Games](/Bangladesh_Games) and [Bengali traditional games](/Bengali_traditional_games)

[Cricket](/Cricket) and [football](/Association_football) are widely popular sports across the Bengal region. Traditional local games include sports such as [Kho Kho](/Kho_Kho) and [Kabaddi](/Kabaddi), with the latter being the national sport of Bangladesh. An Indo-Bangladesh Bengali Games has been organized to foster athletic competition among participants from the Bengali-speaking areas of both countries. [207]